// core layer (design 0009): the two by-value iteration protocols and their step
// enum. These are ORDINARY library definitions — nothing compiler-known: two
// interfaces each spending exactly one associated type (§2.3), and one generic
// enum. The `for` statement desugars to `loop`+`match` over these (§4.2); the
// operand's borrow mode selects the protocol (§4.1).
//
// `Iter` is the consuming protocol: `next(take self)` returns the item alongside
// the successor iterator, dodging swap/replace (§3.1). It is `alloc`-marked,
// uniformly (0007 §4.1): `List::next` must `unbox` its tail, so the marker is
// forced onto the interface — consuming iteration is never the no-alloc floor.
//
// `Indexed` is the borrow-copy protocol: `at(read self, i)` copies an item out of
// a `read` borrow with a loop-owned `usize` cursor (§3.2). It carries NO effect
// marker — a copy-out over a `read` borrow allocates nothing — so `for x in read
// coll` over an `Indexed` collection is the ground-floor, interrupt-callable walk.
use core::opt::{Opt};

pub enum IterStep[T, S] {
    ok More(T, S),
    Done,
}

pub interface Iter {
    type Item;
    fn next(self) alloc -> IterStep[Item, Self];
}

pub interface Indexed {
    type Item;
    fn at(read self, i: usize) -> Opt[Item];
}

// `RefIndexed` is the region-free BORROWED-yield protocol (OBL-ITER-BORROW's
// region-free branch): `for read x in read coll` binds `x` to a `read Item`
// reborrow of each element instead of a copy, so a walk over non-`copy` elements
// need not copy them. It stores no borrow (no iterator object; the cursor is a
// loop-owned `usize`, the collection a loop-local `read` borrow). `get_ref` is
// region-free by 0001 §3.3's compact default: its sole borrow-in is `read self`
// and its sole borrow-out is `read Item`, so the returned reborrow derives from
// `self` with no region variable and nothing storable (no borrow field, 0001
// §3.4). `count` gives the loop bound; both are non-`alloc` (ground floor). One
// associated type (§2.3 intact); two methods (§2.3 caps associated *types*, not
// method count).
pub interface RefIndexed {
    type Item;
    fn count(read self) -> usize;
    fn get_ref(read self, i: usize) -> read Item;
}
